  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me. Growing up in a family where my parents had limited formal education, I never had the same confidence in my academic abilities as my peers who came from more structured learning environments. I remember sitting in high school math class, feeling like I was being judged for not being 'smart enough'—a feeling that's so common for people who fit into stereotypes about their abilities. Stereotype threat is when someone's performance is affected by the fear of confirming a negative stereotype about their group. In STEM, this often means people from underrepresented groups, like women or people of color, might underperform because they're worried about being seen as less capable. I've seen this in my own work as a plumber—when I'm fixing pipes in a building with a lot of engineers, I sometimes feel like I'm not 'smart enough' to understand the technical aspects, even though I've got the skills. But the real issue isn't just about individual anxiety—it's about systemic barriers that make people feel like they don't belong in these fields. Should we address it? Absolutely. The key is to create environments where everyone feels safe to try and make mistakes without fear of judgment. For example, in my community, we have programs that encourage hands-on learning in STEM through workshops that focus on practical skills rather than theoretical knowledge. This helps people see that STEM isn't just about complex equations but about solving real-world problems. I also think it's important to challenge stereotypes directly, like when we talk about how plumbing is a science too—it's not just about fixing leaks but about understanding fluid dynamics. By making STEM accessible and relevant to everyone's daily lives, we can break down those barriers. It's not about changing people's minds—it's about changing the environment so they can thrive.",
